Suspected Data Exfiltration from PIPd Employee

Microsoft Defender for Endpoint Threat Hunt Portfolio Project

Project Overview

This project documents a threat hunt investigation involving a suspected insider threat scenario.

The investigation focused on an employee named John Doe, who worked in a sensitive department and had recently been placed on a performance improvement plan. After management raised concerns that John may attempt to steal proprietary company information before leaving the organization, his corporate device was reviewed for suspicious activity.

The purpose of the hunt was to determine whether company files were being collected, compressed, staged, or exfiltrated from the device.

This investigation used Microsoft Defender for Endpoint telemetry and KQL queries to review:

- File archive activity
- Zip file creation
- PowerShell activity
- 7zip installation and execution
- Local data staging
- Network activity around the time of suspicious file activity
- Possible data exfiltration
- MITRE ATT&CK technique mapping
- Remediation and improvement steps

Scenario Summary

Management raised concern that an employee in a sensitive role may attempt to steal proprietary information after being placed on a performance improvement plan.

The employee had administrator rights on his device and was not heavily restricted in which applications could be used. This created a risk that the employee could install archiving tools, compress company data, stage the files locally, and attempt to move them to a private drive or external destination.

The investigation focused on whether the employee archived sensitive data and whether there was evidence that the archived data left the device.

